To further evaluate the applicability of the obtained 2D-AgNPs/CDs in SERS. They are applied in the detection of thiram, a commonly used fungicide in apple [33,34]. The thiram exhibits strong SERS signals even at low concentrations (Fig. 5
                        a). There is a good semi-logarithmic correlation between the SERS intensity at 1384 cm−1 and the concentration of thiram in the range from 0.01 ppb to 1 ppm (Fig. 5b). The detection limit is calculated to be 3.9 ppt. Then the 2D-AgNPs/CDs were further used to measure the residual thiram in apple juice. The residual thiram in the apple juice is lower than the detection limit. Thus, the apple juice was spiked with thiram of different concentrations. It can be found that the matrix of apple juice affects the SERS spectra of thiram in some degree. However, the main Raman peaks of thiram have no obvious change (Fig. 5c). Furthermore, the linear response range of thiram in apple juice is similar with that in water (Fig. 5d). Based on the results, a spike-and-recovery experience was carried out. The satisfactory recoveries suggest a good reliability of the method (Table 1
                        ).
